******
[2]
Date: Wed 14 May 2014
Source: KCRA Sacramento [edited]
http://www.kcra.com/news/more-sleeping-tb-cases-discovered-at-high-school/25984888


More than 100 students at Grant High School in Sacramento have been diagnosed with a "sleeping" [latent] version of tuberculosis. Health officials have now started testing students in classrooms that are connected by air-conditioning ducts.

The students have been put on a 12-week course of medications to keep the latent TB from becoming active and impacting their health.

Health officials say latent TB is not contagious, but active TB can be passed through the air.

Health officials first started testing students in early March [2014] after one student was diagnosed with active TB.

Health officials say it can be difficult sometimes to convince people with the dormant form of TB to follow through on their medications. "A lot of people who are diagnosed with latent TB infection are feeling well, and you are asking them to take this medication which is quite strong. That is why the education piece is very important," said Sacramento County Public Health Officer Dr Olivia Kasirye.

The health department says some of the dormant cases weren't discovered until officials re-examined the air-conditioning system and started testing students who were in classrooms connected by air ducts.

Health officials are working with students to make sure the students don't miss a dose, but say it will become more complicated once school lets out for the summer. "We do have a team of people with the health department who are keeping track, and we are working with the school making sure those that are being treated get their treatment every week," Kasirye said. The health department pays for the medications because it is considered a public health threat, officials said.

[Byline: Kevin Oliver]

