[Since the 1992 TB resurgence peak in the United States, the number of tuberculosis (TB) cases reported annually has decreased and the number of reported TB cases in 2012 was the lowest recorded since national reporting began in 1953 (http://www.cdc.gov/tb/statistics/reports/2012/pdf/report2012.pdf). However, in 2012 the rate in California was higher (5.8) than the national average rate of 3.2 cases per 100 000 persons and the percent of TB cases occurring among foreign-born persons (78) was higher than the national average, 63 percent; 37 percent were of Hispanic and 44 percent were of Asian ethnicity (http://www.cdc.gov/tb/statistics/reports/2012/pdf/report2012.pdf).

The 2 news reports do not mention how the index case, an adolescent who was diagnosed with active TB in early March 2014, contracted the illness. Children most commonly develop TB as a result of exposure to a case of active pulmonary TB in their immediate environment, usually in their household.

TB is caused by _Mycobacterium tuberculosis_ (Mtb) that are spread in airborne droplets. People usually acquire TB from another person who has active, most often cavitary, pulmonary TB. Lung cavities tend to contain high numbers of _M. tuberculosis_ (Mtb). When patients with lung cavities cough or sneeze, large numbers of infectious aerosols are expelled into the surrounding air. The degree of contagiousness of the patient is indicated by the number of bacilli seen on smears of sputum stained specifically for mycobacteria, that is, acid-fast bacilli (AFB). Transmission of TB depends on the concentration and size of infectious particles, the proximity to the patient, ventilation of the space in which exposure takes place, and duration of exposure, as well as characteristics of the specific strain. The closer and the longer the duration of exposure in poorly ventilated spaces, the higher is the risk for transmission.

The 2nd news reports says that some of the latent TB cases weren't discovered until officials re-examined the air-conditioning system and started testing students who were in classrooms connected by air ducts. Airborne transmission of Mtb via air ventilation ducts was demonstrated many years ago using guinea pigs to detect the airborne Mtb (Riley, R, et al: Aerial dissemination of pulmonary tuberculosis. A two year study of contagion in a tuberculosis ward. Am J Hyg 1959; 70: 185-196. Available at http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/content/142/1/3.full.pdf+html?ijkey=497aeea8bed8d0da92926ff5b3d09891108588ce&keytype2=tf_ipsecsha subscription required).

Following inhalation of infectious aerosols of Mtb, primary pulmonary Mtb infection develops with subsequent hematogenous dissemination to the lungs and other organs, usually without evoking any symptoms. Activation of latent Mtb infection can occur at a later time, especially if the individual becomes malnourished, develops an immunosuppressive illness such as HIV infection or receives immunosuppressive medication such as a corticosteroid. About 10 percent of people with latent TB will develop active TB at some point in their lives. However, adolescents are more susceptible to develop active TB, and the time between initial infection and development of active TB is shorter (Wilcox W, Laufer S: Tuberculosis in adolescents. Clin Pediatr 1994; 33: 258-62; and Smith MHD: Tuberculosis in adolescents. Clin Pediatr 1967; 6: 9-15). Nevertheless, many adolescents fail to complete a course of therapy for latent TB (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1497389/pdf/12196616.pdf).

In 1965, we described a large outbreak of TB that started in the fall of 1962 among medical students (11 cases) and employees of the medical school (11 cases) and medical college hospital (5 cases) (Alpert ME, Levison ME: An epidemic of tuberculosis in a medical school. N Engl J Med 1965; 272: 7l8-21). In the medical school classes in which cases of TB occurred, the tuberculin skin test reactivity rose from 16 percent on average among medical students at admission to medical school to 69-90 percent among those students that had not been vaccinated with BCG on admission. No one source was identified in this medical school outbreak, but school outbreaks should serve as a reminder that students, especially young children, serve as indicators of recent transmission that warrants prompt investigation for a source with active tuberculosis in their environment so that further transmission can be rapidly interrupted. - Mod.ML

